Wind has lots of potential, but if you start producing more than about 20 percent of your power with wind, you better have a really good transmission network.  Otherwise, a low pressure system is going to kill your standard of living.<br>
<br>
But lets suppose we go 20 percent wind to displace 20 percent coal power.  That takes the coal fraction  (in the USA) to 39 percent.  Can natgas make up that entire 39 percent?  <br>
<br>
IF hydrates in the Gulf pan out, I guess they could, but carbon sequestration becomes a real problem....<br>
<br>
 But you also believe nuclear is fading out, so you want to also use natgas for 19 percent more, or a total of 58 percent?<br>
<br>
Nah, let's have solar take some of the slack, say 5 percent.  The over-night problems of solar will keep it from getting much higher than that, I firmly believe....<br>
<br>
So, natural gas is to provide 50 percent of our electricity, wind 20 percent, hydro 10 or so, solar 5 percent?  That's 85 percent, and efficiency should be able to cover that. <br>
<br>
Sounds doable! <br>
<br>
Now, how do you price this, and how do we grow in the future?  Also, how do we power cars?  Keep importing oil, or run them on natgas?<br>
<br>
Plus, we have to get the CO2 down.....<br>
<br>
