<br>
Natgas plants are not that cheep, and are tied to the supply of gas. The reason coal prevails is that it is cheep, since we have an abundant amount. Coal and nuclear make up nearly 70% of power production for a reason.<br>
<br>
Secretary Abrams wants to see new nuclear plants by the end of the decade. The US changed its permitting requirements for nuclear plants during the 1990's to remove some of the unnecessarily burdensome regulations, such as banning using a standard design, and changed the system to be more like those in Europe, still safe but with less red tape. No plant has been built under the new regulations, but they should dramatically reduce construction costs and build times.<br>
<br>
Geo, hydro, and wind should be used when they can, and we should use natgas to suppliment nuclear, slowly phasing out coal and oil. <p>"If," he wispered, "if we could only pick that lock...." - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2212<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/8/02 6:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=74.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  How disapointing.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> You are putting completely bogus words in my mouth. Stop it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
